concerted effort to achieve access to safe and adequate water and sanitation service, to-date there is a lack of focused attention to demonstrate how to realise universal access scenario in a location, as an example to inspire national scale up. It is generally believed that urban areas will increase in number, population and importance. Improving our understanding of how sustainable universal sanitation services can be provided in small towns or urban growth centres will remain high on the agenda, or even rise in the years to come.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">This study therefore aims to contribute to answering the largely unanswered question in urban sanitation - how to identify which service delivery model to apply where and at what scale? The research project will to contribute to the sectors understanding of how to achieve sustainable universal access to sanitation services in Babati, Town, with a view to eventually up-scaling this lessons on sanitation in other urban areas of the country. Secondly, the study will demonstrate the conditions under which municipalities and citizens can co-produce and implement a town-wide sanitation plan that can deliver inclusive and sustainable sanitation services to all.&nbsp;</span></p> <p style="background: rgb(103, 103, 103); margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><b><span style="color: white; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">2. What?</span></b></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">This study focuses on answering the largely unanswered question in urban sanitation - how to identify which service delivery model to apply where and at what scale? The research project will to contribute to the sectors understanding of how to achieve sustainable universal access to sanitation services in Babati, Town, with a view to eventually up-scaling this lessons on sanitation in other urban areas of the country. Secondly, the study will demonstrate the conditions under which municipalities and citizens can co-produce and implement a town-wide sanitation plan that can deliver inclusive and sustainable sanitation services to all. Through cross-sectional study using both qualitative and quantitative methods will be applied to understand: 1) what motivates and drives people (households) to invest in and improve sanitation and hygiene practices in an urban context; 2) what drives institutions (government, donors, NGOs, authorities), and private sectors to invest and/or improve sanitation and hygiene practices in an urban context; 3) the main economics, social, political and institutional determinants of success for urban authorities to design and implement an inclusive sanitation and hygiene plan; and 4) the risks and potential factors (including public health hazards) that relates (drive) hygiene and sanitation behaviour change. In addition, the study will contribute to development of Babati town-wide sanitation and hygiene adaptive master plan that promotes inclusive, sustainable and affordable hygiene and sanitation services for all.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">To achieve these the study will consist of five phases described in detail below.-</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Phase 1: Inception–&nbsp;This phase will include procurement of resources and a small project launch workshop. This time will also be used to gaining-country ethics&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; approval.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Phase 2: Data collection &amp; diagnostic – This phase will include the secondary and primary data collecting, cleaning and analysis, as well as development of relevant learning notes, briefing papers and manuscripts.&nbsp;-</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Phase 3:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Participatory planning and scenario building – This phase will be working closely with all stakeholders to jointly reflect on the data collected and use this to identify key planning strategies, actions and goals, as well as build modules for a range of scenarios.-</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Phase 4: Town-wide sanitation and hygiene plan – During this phase stakeholders will agree on the scenario(s) to be included in the town-wide sanitation and hygiene plan. The plan will be officially signed-off by the Town Council and harmonised with financial resources and investment plans, enabling framework; operation plans assumptions, risks and monitoring and evaluation plans.-</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Phase 5: Learning and dissemination –This will be an on-going process, continuous through all four phases above. Learning notes and research papers; pathways to town-wide sanitation and conditions for scale-up. Published papers in academic / scientific journals would be an indicator of success of the contract with the academic research institution and consultant / mentor</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><b><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Estimated cost</span></b><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;– This project is full funded</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><b><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Estimated timeframe</span></b><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;– The project duration is 36 months&nbsp;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;"><b>sting WaterAid experience</b>&nbsp;– New innovation / less than 2 years’ experience / more than 2 years’ experience</span></p> <p style="background: rgb(103, 103, 103); margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><b><span style="color: white; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">3. Where?</span></b></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;This project will benefit the residents of Babati, which is situated in situated in the Rift Valley. The Town of Babati has a population of 93,108 (2012) and sits at a cross road between Arusha, Singida, Dodoma, Mbulu and Simanjiro, covering an area of 460.86km2.&nbsp; The Region of Manyara was established in 2002 and Babati Town announced as the regional headquarter in 2004. On the other side the findings from this research will benefit &nbsp;the WASH sector as whole, it is anticipated that other districts or councils will learn from this study.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">&nbsp;</span></p> <p style="background: rgb(103, 103, 103); margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><b><span style="color: white; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">4. Who?</span></b></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The Regional Administrative Secretary (RAS)</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">will generally coordinate and oversee the implementation of the programme in all the LGAs within the region. More specifically, the RAS will have the following critical roles and responsibilities: (a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Technical backstopping of the LGAs in the implementation of all aspects of the programme; (b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Providing hands-on facilitation and other technical support in the implementation of capacity buildi